                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/14346.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister to Mexico</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-02-06T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 6, 1915—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>443. Your 303, February 3, 5 p.m. Department thinks it important in the matter of
                    withdrawal that unanimity should prevail <pb facs="0768" n="652" xml:id="pg_652"
                    /> among the entire Diplomatic Corps now in Mexico City as far as possible. It
                    is assumed that you will receive suitable instructions as to the course you
                    should pursue from your Government, but you may say to Silliman and to all
                    American employees of your Legation that they may consider themselves at liberty
                    to withdraw from Mexico City whenever a majority of the Diplomatic Corps,
                    including yourself, deems it advisable to withdraw. In case of sudden departure
                    of Diplomatic Corps, you may ship archives to Consulate at Vera Cruz, if
                    possible; otherwise, make such disposition as in your judgment may be deemed
                    most appropriate. It is earnestly hoped that representations which have been
                    made to General Carranza at Vera Cruz will make withdrawal unnecessary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
